This paper is about a neural language model that learns to discover semantically meaningful units from unsegmented character sequences. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the natural language processing (NLP) sub-category of computer science, which is cs.CL. Additionally, the paper combines the representational power of neural networks and the structure learning mechanism of Bayesian nonparametrics, which suggests that it could also belong to the machine learning (ML) sub-category of computer science, which is cs.LG. The paper also introduces a differentiable regularizer to prevent the model from overusing the lexical memory, which suggests that it could belong to the artificial intelligence (AI) sub-category of computer science, which is cs.AI. Furthermore, the paper generates text as a sequence of segments, which suggests that it could belong to the neural networks (NE) sub-category of computer science, which is cs.NE. Finally, the paper could also belong to the computer vision (CV) sub-category of computer science, as it deals with discovering semantically meaningful units from unsegmented character sequences, which is a task that is relevant to image segmentation and object recognition.
